Summary: 
Jim Simons (1938–2024) was an immensely successful American hedge fund manager, mathematician, and philanthropist. He founded Renaissance Technologies, a highly lucrative quantitative hedge fund, earning him the reputation of the greatest investor on Wall Street, with an estimated net worth of $31.4 billion at the time of his death. Academically, he is renowned for co-developing the Chern-Simons form, which significantly impacted string theory and quantum field theory. He served on the Harvard University mathematics faculty and was a member of prestigious academic organizations including the National Academy of Sciences, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and the American Philosophical Society, as well as a trustee of the Institute for Advanced Study. Philanthropically, he and his wife established the Simons Foundation, providing massive financial support to scientific research and educational institutions such as Stony Brook University, MIT, and UC Berkeley. Additionally, he was associated with the Madoff investment scandal and named in the Paradise Papers.
