Evidence in page: 
John von Neumann (...; December 28, 1903 – February 8, 1957) was a Hungarian and American mathematician, physicist, computer scientist and engineer. Von Neumann had perhaps the widest coverage of any mathematician of his time, integrating pure and applied sciences and making major contributions to many fields, including mathematics, physics, economics, computing, and statistics. He was a pioneer in building the mathematical framework of quantum physics, in the development of functional analysis, and in game theory, introducing or codifying concepts including cellular automata, the universal constructor and the digital computer. His analysis of the structure of self-replication preceded the discovery of the structure of DNA. During World War II, von Neumann worked on the Manhattan Project. He developed the mathematical models behind the explosive lenses used in the implosion-type nuclear weapon... He was also a member of the influential Atomic Energy Commission in charge of all atomic energy development in the country. Von Neumann was born in Budapest, Kingdom of Hungary (then part of Austria-Hungary)... on December 28, 1903, to a wealthy, non-observant Jewish family, and as noted in the categories, he later converted to Roman Catholicism. Von Neumann was a child prodigy. His research into weather systems and meteorological prediction led him to propose manipulating the environment by spreading colorants on the polar ice caps to enhance absorption of solar radiation... He also warned that weather and climate control could have military uses. The first use of the concept of a singularity in the technological context is attributed to von Neumann. Von Neumann made his principal contribution to the atomic bomb in the concept and design of the explosive lenses that were needed to compress the plutonium core of the Fat Man weapon that was later dropped on Nagasaki. He collaborated with Klaus Fuchs on further development of the bomb, and in 1946 the two filed a secret patent outlining a scheme for using a fission bomb to compress fusion fuel to initiate nuclear fusion. Now either chairing or serving on several boards dealing with strategic missiles and nuclear weaponry, von Neumann was able to inject several crucial arguments regarding potential Soviet advancements... to argue for the creation of Intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs). During a Senate committee hearing he described his political ideology as "violently anti-communist". Von Neumann was also noted for his eidetic memory, particularly of the symbolic kind. Von Neumann's mathematical fluency, calculation speed, and general problem-solving ability were widely noted by his peers. He is widely regarded as one of the greatest and most influential mathematicians and scientists of the 20th century. As a result of his wide reaching influence and contributions to many fields, he is widely considered a polymath. He married Mariette Kövesi in 1930... The couple had one daughter, Marina von Neumann Whitman... He later married Klara Dan. According to the categorical listings, he was affiliated with the University of Göttingen, University of Hamburg, Princeton University, and the Institute for Advanced Study. He was a recipient of the Medal for Merit, Medal of Freedom, Enrico Fermi Award, and the Carl-Gustaf Rossby Research Medal. The webpage content also consists of a vast bibliography and further reading section citing von Neumann's original papers, books, and numerous biographies such as 'The Man from the Future', 'Turing's Cathedral', and 'John von Neumann: The Scientific Genius Who Pioneered the Modern Computer, Game Theory, Nuclear Deterrence, and Much More'.

Summary: 
John von Neumann (1903–1957) was a renowned Hungarian-American mathematician, physicist, computer scientist, and engineer. Recognized as a child prodigy with an eidetic memory and unmatched calculation speed, he is widely regarded as one of the greatest polymaths and scientists of the 20th century. Born to a Jewish family, he later converted to Roman Catholicism. Throughout his career, he held academic positions at prestigious institutions like the University of Göttingen, Princeton University, and the Institute for Advanced Study. He made profound contributions to numerous fields, pioneering the mathematical framework of quantum mechanics, functional analysis, and game theory, and was instrumental in the development of the digital computer, cellular automata, and the universal constructor. He is also credited with first using the concept of a "technological singularity" and warned about the military implications of climate control. During World War II, he contributed significantly to the Manhattan Project by developing mathematical models for the explosive lenses used in the Fat Man atomic bomb and later co-patented a mechanism for the hydrogen bomb. Violently anti-communist, he became a central defense consultant postwar, serving on the Atomic Energy Commission and playing a leading role in championing the United States' ICBM programs. His legacy is celebrated through numerous prestigious awards, including the Medal for Merit, Medal of Freedom, and Enrico Fermi Award, as well as a lunar crater and an asteroid named in his honor. His extensive bibliography, numerous biographies, and the vast secondary literature dedicated to his work further highlight his foundational impact on diverse disciplines. He was married twice and had one daughter, Marina von Neumann Whitman.
