Summary: 
Michael Atiyah (born April 22, 1929, in Hampstead; died January 11, 2019, in Edinburgh) was a prominent British mathematician and topologist. He made significant contributions to topology, geometry, and mathematics, including notable works like the Atiyah-Singer index theorem. He was educated at Trinity College, the University of Cambridge, and other institutions, and was advised by W. V. D. Hodge. Throughout his distinguished career, he taught at the University of Cambridge and the University of Oxford, and served as President of the Royal Society. His exceptional work earned him numerous prestigious awards, including the Fields Medal in 1966, the Copley Medal in 1988, and the Abel Prize in 2004.
