Summary: 
Nathan Jacobson (1910–1999) was a prominent American mathematician known for his work in algebra. Born in Warsaw in the Russian Empire, he moved to the United States and became a citizen. He received his education at the University of Alabama and earned his doctorate from Princeton University under the advisement of Joseph Wedderburn. Jacobson held academic positions at several prestigious institutions, notably Yale University (1947–1981), Johns Hopkins University, and the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill. His major contributions to mathematics include the Jacobson density theorem, the Jacobson radical, and the Jacobson-Bourbaki theorem. He was honored with a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1951 and the Steele Prize for Lifetime Achievement in 1998.
