Summary: 
Heinz Hopf (1894–1971) was a renowned German mathematician and topologist who held citizenship in both Germany and Switzerland. Educated at prestigious institutions including the University of Berlin, Göttingen, and Wrocław, he later worked primarily at ETH Zurich as a university teacher. Hopf made profound contributions to mathematics, specifically in differential geometry, algebraic topology, and geometry. He is best known for his foundational concepts such as the Hopf fibration, Hopf algebra, Poincaré–Hopf theorem, and Hopf link. During his lifetime, he received multiple honors, including the Lobachevsky Prize, and was an elected member of several esteemed academic societies, such as the German Academy of Sciences Leopoldina and the National Academy of Sciences.
