Summary: 
Abram Isaakovich Alikhanov (born Abraham Alikhanian; 1904–1970) was a distinguished Soviet experimental physicist of Armenian descent, specializing in particle and nuclear physics. He was a major contributor to the Soviet atomic bomb project and the founder of the Institute for Theoretical and Experimental Physics (ITEP), which he directed from 1945 to 1968. Alikhanov led the development of the Soviet Union's first research and industrial heavy water reactors. He also pioneered Soviet accelerator technology, co-creating a 'baby cyclotron' with Igor Kurchatov in 1934 and spearheading the construction of the 70 GeV synchrotron in Serpukhov in 1967, which was the largest in the world at the time. A Full Member of the USSR Academy of Sciences, he was highly decorated for his contributions, receiving honors such as Hero of Socialist Labour, the Order of Lenin, the Order of the Red Banner of Labour, and the Stalin Prize. He is buried at the Novodevichy Cemetery in Moscow.
