Evidence in page: 
Andrei Sergeyevich Monin (July 2, 1921 – September 22, 2007) was a Soviet and Russian geophysicist, mathematician, and oceanographer. Monin was known for his contributions to statistical theory of turbulence and atmospheric physics. He served as the director of the P.P. Shirshov Institute of Oceanology of the Academy of Sciences of the Soviet Union. The Monin–Obukhov similarity theory and the Monin–Obukhov length are named after Monin and Russian Academician Alexander Obukhov.

He joined the Mechanical and Mathematical Faculty of the Lomonosov Moscow State University in 1938 and received his bachelor's degree in 1942. In 1943, Monin was called up for military service in the ranks of the Red Army where he was asked to join the military courses of weather forecasters. In 1946, Monin came back to Moscow State University to continue his post-graduate programme under the direct guidance of Academician Andrey Kolmogorov who prepared and defended his Candidate's thesis on the theory of atmospheric turbulence.

A. S. Monin had received many honors and medals: among them are: Foreign member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, 1973. Foreign member of the United States National Academy of Sciences, 1976... USSR State Prize, 1980. Yuly Shokalsky Prize, 1986. Alexander Friedmann Prize by Russian Academy of Sciences in 1993.

He was the author of about 620 scientific publications... Noted for its clarity as well as its comprehensive treatment, the book "Statistical Fluid Mechanics: Mechanics of Turbulence", co-authored with Akiva Yaglom, is considered to be a classic work on theory of turbulence.

Summary: 
Andrei Monin (1921-2007) was a prominent Soviet and Russian geophysicist, mathematician, and oceanographer. He is best known for his work in atmospheric physics and turbulence, particularly the Monin-Obukhov similarity theory and length. He was directed by Andrey Kolmogorov during his post-graduate studies at Moscow State University. Monin served in the Red Army as a weather forecaster during WWII and later became the director of the Shirshov Institute of Oceanology. He received numerous accolades, including the USSR State Prize and the Alexander Friedmann Prize, and co-authored the classic book 'Statistical Fluid Mechanics' with Akiva Yaglom. This comprehensive profile can be used to cross-reference against specific clues.
