Akiva Moiseevich Yaglom (March 6, 1921, Kharkiv, Ukraine – December 13, 2007, Boston, Massachusetts) was a prominent Soviet and Russian physicist, mathematician, statistician, and meteorologist. He is best known for his work in the statistical theory of turbulence and random processes. He had a twin brother, Isaak Yaglom, who was also a mathematician. Yaglom studied under Andrey Kolmogorov and worked at institutions including Moscow State University, the Steklov Institute of Mathematics, the USSR Academy of Sciences, and later the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). He was awarded the Otto Laporte Award in 1988 and the Lewis Fry Richardson Medal posthumously in 2008. This profile provides comprehensive facts that can be cross-referenced with the user's specific clues.
