Summary: 
Israel Moiseevich Gelfand (September 2, 1913 – October 5, 2009) was a prominent Ukrainian-American mathematician and biologist. Born into a Jewish family in Ukraine, he received his PhD in 1935 and later immigrated to the US in 1989. He is widely considered one of the greatest mathematicians of the 20th century, making significant contributions to group theory, representation theory, and functional analysis. Throughout his career, he worked at Moscow State University and Rutgers University. He received numerous prestigious awards, including the Order of Lenin (three times), the first Wolf Prize (1978), the Kyoto Prize (1989), and a MacArthur Fellowship (1994). He died at the age of 96 in New Jersey.
